    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4199473615" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4199473615" />
    <a title="Damini" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45223486-damini"><img alt="Damini" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641142467p2/45223486.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4199473615?book_show_action=true">Jan 29, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Damini" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Damini" href="/user/show/45223486-damini">Damini</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45223486-damini?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45223486-damini?shelf=political">political</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45223486-damini?shelf=wfh">wfh</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45223486-damini?shelf=atoz22">atoz22</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45223486-damini?shelf=nonfic">nonfic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45223486-damini?shelf=2022">2022</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4199473615" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3650821973052430231">If you’ve ever seen the movie ‘The Post’, and Meryl Streep’s and Tom Hanks’ characters’ determination to publish an expose impressed you, I invite you to read this book. <br/><br/>In ‘Manufacturing Consent’, the authors blow away the cobwebs from the theory that’s been sitting in people’s minds for so long, that privatised media in the United States is free and fair. That it regularly showcases dissent towards the state authorities, and champions people’s voices and opinions. They then take this theory, a</span>
  <span id="freeText3650821973052430231" style="display:none">If you’ve ever seen the movie ‘The Post’, and Meryl Streep’s and Tom Hanks’ characters’ determination to publish an expose impressed you, I invite you to read this book. <br /><br />In ‘Manufacturing Consent’, the authors blow away the cobwebs from the theory that’s been sitting in people’s minds for so long, that privatised media in the United States is free and fair. That it regularly showcases dissent towards the state authorities, and champions people’s voices and opinions. They then take this theory, and chuck it down the garbage chute. Because obviously not! So long as media remains in the control of elite groups, it is never going to be independent; it will always serve said elite group’s interest – and, by extension, the US government’s. <br /><br />Chomsky and Herman begin by building a propaganda model that contains certain filters that every news item goes through, and if the item it makes it to the end, bam – what we’ve got is mostly propaganda. To prove the working of this model, they talk about the cases where accusations against the media, of dissent and govt critique, were the highest. In a highly researched manner, they pick apart this prevalent myth to showcase how in each of these cases, the papers and tv channels picked and chose the news items that they thought were worthy of communication to the public. Naturally, these pieces were also phrased in such a manner (complete with apathy, falsified facts and blind adherence to the state provided documents) that painted current events in the light that the US govt wanted to portray. For instance – and this will continue to infuriate me forever, I think – the American escalation of the Vietnam War, contrary to Hollywood’s portrayal (I’m looking at you, “Trial of the Chicago Seven”, and of course, the movie mentioned in the opening statement of this review, AND, of course, countless others) was supported and cheered on by mass media and the general populace pre-1968’s Tet offensive. After that, the gradual turn of public opinion against the war, egged on by 'dissenting' media, was more along the lines of “our boys are dying”, rather than, you know, the Big Daddy of Democracy Defenders has basically inserted itself and purposefully created a military conflict in ANOTHER COUNTRY and is killing the NATIVE population of said country. But, of course, the media won’t talk about this – since, as Chomsky and Herman prove eloquently, it is currently serving lobbyist, and by extension, the US govt’s, interests.<br /><br />This book is eye opening. It doesn’t necessarily change your life, or put forward a theory that you didn’t already know (in my native language, we call it “news biki hui hai”, or “the news is sold out”, and, well, everyone across the entire political spectrum is aware of this). But it certainly plants the seed of critique and awareness in your mind, so that you stop accepting every news item as objective fact, and maybe start scrutinising the phrasing, the sources, and most importantly, the intent behind it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3650821973052430231" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


